International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC)

In Bangladesh, the ICRC helps people affected by violence, promotes IHL, enhances physical rehabilitation services and supports the Bangladesh Red Crescent. With the Bangladesh Red Crescent, we reunite missing people with their families and facilitate the repatriation of migrants.

In Eritrea, the ICRC responds to problems linked to the 1998 war between Eritrea and Ethiopia. We help people in rural areas and those affected by the armed conflict and ensure compliance with international humanitarian law.

In Armenia, the ICRC helps mine victims, missing persons and their families, and communities living along the border with Azerbaijan. We also visit detainees held for conflict-related or security reasons, or who are otherwise vulnerable.In Armenia, the ICRC helps mine victims, missing persons and their families, and communities living along the border with Azerbaijan. We also visit detainees held for conflict-related or security reasons, or who are otherwise vulnerable.

In Azerbaijan, the ICRC supports the families of missing persons and helps detainees held for conflict-related or security reasons, or who are otherwise vulnerable. We respond to such health issues as tuberculosis in prisons, and we monitor the situation of communities along the border with Armenia.

In Burundi, the ICRC repairs water and sanitation systems, restores family links and reunites families. We work with prison authorities to ensure that detainees are treated according to internationally recognized standards and support training in international humanitarian law for the armed forces.

In Egypt, the ICRC promotes respect for international humanitarian law in the member countries of the League of Arab States. The delegation has also worked with the Egyptian Red Crescent to help people uprooted by the Libya conflict and provided first aid to people injured in violence within Egypt.

Decades of armed conflict have left 8.8 million victims in Colombia. Urgent humanitarian challenges include: supporting communities affected by violence, helping the families of missing people, and advocating for the protection of migrants.Decades of armed conflict have left 8.8 million victims in Colombia. Urgent humanitarian challenges include: supporting communities affected by violence, helping the families of missing people, and advocating for the protection of migrants.

ICRC headquarters in Geneva supports our delegations around the world. Geneva also manages the ICRC's role of advocate and defender of IHL, dealing with governments and with partners in the humanitarian community. Headquarters manages funding appeals, human resources and global communications.

In Australia, the ICRC fosters support for our global operations and promotes international humanitarian law and universal humanitarian principles. Overview of activities in Australia The ICRC's Suva delegation promotes international humanitarian law and raises other humanitarian issues with governments, security forces, academic circles, the media and civil society. We help communities affected by conflict, visit detainees and support the region's National Societies.
